      <div class="bg-white p-8 border-[3px] spd-border">
        <h4 class="text-2xl font-black mb-4" style="color: #22C55E;">CRITICAL CSS EXTRACTION</h4>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 mb-4">
          <span class="font-bold">The technique:</span> Above-the-fold content (what users see initially)
          should render immediately. Non-critical CSS can load later. Critical CSS extraction
          identifies render-blocking CSS and inlines it in HTML. Rest loads asynchronously.
        </p>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 mb-4">
          <span class="font-bold">How it works:</span> Tools extract CSS used for above-fold content, inline
          it in &lt;style&gt; tag in HTML head. Remaining CSS loads via async link. First paint
          happens faster because critical styles are available immediately.
        </p>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 mb-4">
          <span class="font-bold">When it matters:</span> Large CSS files (200KB+). Complex sites with
          multiple pages using different styles. For simple AI builder sites with minimal CSS,
          this is overkill.
        </p>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 mb-4">
          <span class="font-bold">Real example:</span> E-commerce site had 450KB CSS file. First Contentful
          Paint (FCP): 3.2 seconds. Extracted critical CSS (45KB inline). FCP dropped to 1.4
          seconds. Largest Contentful Paint (LCP) unchanged (2.8 seconds), but perceived performance
          improved. Visitors saw content faster, felt site was faster even though total load time
          unchanged.
        </p>
        <p class="font-bold text-green-700">
          Critical CSS = faster perceived load. Complex sites only.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white p-8 border-[3px] spd-border">
        <h4 class="text-2xl font-black mb-4" style="color: #22C55E;">JAVASCRIPT DEFERRAL & ASYNC</h4>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 mb-4">
          <span class="font-bold">The problem:</span> JavaScript blocks rendering. Browser sees
          &lt;script&gt; tag, stops rendering, downloads and executes JS, then continues. Large
          JS files or slow servers = delayed content.
        </p>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 mb-4">
          <span class="font-bold">The solutions:</span> Defer (download in background, execute after HTML
          parsing). Async (download in background, execute when ready). Use defer for non-critical
          JS. Use async for independent JS (analytics, chat widgets).
        </p>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 mb-4">
          <span class="font-bold">Builder implementation:</span> Framer and Durable handle this automatically.
          Webflow allows manual control. Wix/Squarespace manage internally. If using custom scripts,
          add defer/async attributes manually.
        </p>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 mb-4">
          <span class="font-bold">Real example:</span> Landing page loaded Google Analytics, Facebook Pixel,
          Hotjar, Intercom chat before main content. Total JS: 380KB. LCP: 4.1 seconds. Deferral:
          analytics deferred, chat widgets async-loaded after 3 seconds. LCP: 2.3 seconds. Same
          scripts, smarter loading = 1.8 second faster.
        </p>
        <p class="font-bold text-green-700">
          Defer non-critical JS. Async load independent widgets.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white p-8 border-[3px] spd-border">
        <h4 class="text-2xl font-black mb-4" style="color: #22C55E;">PRELOADING KEY RESOURCES</h4>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 mb-4">
          <span class="font-bold">The technique:</span> Browser discovers resources as it parses HTML.
          Key resources (hero image, critical CSS, critical fonts) aren't discovered until late in
          parsing. Preload hints tell browser to start downloading these resources immediately.
        </p>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 mb-4">
          <span class="font-bold">Preload types:</span> &lt;link rel="preload" as="image"&gt; for hero images.
          &lt;link rel="preload" as="font"&gt; for critical fonts. &lt;link rel="preload" as="style"&gt;
          for critical CSS. Each resource type has specific preload syntax.
        </p>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 mb-4">
          <span class="font-bold">When it matters:</span> Hero images larger than 200KB. Custom fonts
          used above fold. Sites where LCP is image/font-heavy. For text-heavy pages with system
          fonts, preloading adds unnecessary complexity.
        </p>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 mb-4">
          <span class="font-bold">Real example:</span> Portfolio site had 840KB hero image (photographer
          high-res work). LCP: 4.7 seconds (wait for image discovery + download). Added preload
          hint in HTML head. Image started downloading immediately (not waited for parser to discover).
          LCP dropped to 3.1 seconds. 1.6 second improvement from one line of code.
        </p>
        <p class="font-bold text-green-700">
          Preload key resources. Don't preload everything.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-white p-8 border-[3px] spd-border">
        <h4 class="text-2xl font-black mb-4" style="color: #22C55E;">CODE SPLITTING & LAZY LOADING</h4>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 mb-4">
          <span class="font-bold">The technique:</span> Load only JavaScript needed for current page.
          Other page JS loads when user navigates there. Images below fold load as user scrolls.
          Reduces initial page weight dramatically.
        </p>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 mb-4">
          <span class="font-bold">Code splitting:</span> Single-page apps bundle all JS together.
          Code splitting creates route-specific bundles. Homepage loads homepage JS only. About page
          loads about JS only. Initial load 60-80% smaller.
        </p>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 mb-4">
          <span class="font-bold">Lazy loading images:</span> Images below fold aren't visible initially.
          Don't load them until needed. Browser loads images as user scrolls. Initial page weight
          drops 40-60%. LCP improves (browser focuses on hero image, not distracted by offscreen
          images).
        </p>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 mb-4">
          <span class="font-bold">Real example:</span> Blog had 15 images per article. All images loaded
          immediately (3.2MB total). LCP: 4.2 seconds (competing with hero image). Lazy loading:
          only 3 initial images loaded (640KB). LCP: 2.1 seconds. Same content, 2.1 second faster. Bounce
          rate dropped from 68% to 51% (faster load = fewer abandonments).
        </p>
        <p class="font-bold text-green-700">
          Load what's visible now. Load rest as needed.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

